{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b597e738-7b1c-45d9-87f0-1d405e6842fa","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings your MAUI workload back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or partially-installed workloads but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still get errors after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-*`) appears, and check that your project's `<TargetFramework>` matches the SDK version you have installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ef2f03c4-a148-4074-a51f-67a63f59096e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":255,"requestId":"A422:2231E4:5BB61D0:642CBF3:69F00420"},"id":"29ec36ca-ba7b-4663-b953-aea1304bc98d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:49:44.051Z","parentId":"a2b01aa8-c7ac-4d31-9950-6c3e858ac88f"}
